<article>

  <p>
    A meal arrives that is exactly what was wanted. For a few bites, the mind
    settles as if it had found ground. Then the flavor dulls, the body shifts,
    a notification interrupts, and the same mind that was resting starts hunting
    again. The afternoon is a relay of wanting and not-wanting. None of the usual
    unfinished business of a life cancels a quieter fact: if experience is met as
    though it will hold, satisfy, and belong to a fixed owner, ordinary change
    becomes a private quarrel.
  </p>

  <p>
    The Buddha's name for that territory is the three characteristics —
    <span class="pali" data-pali="ti-lakkhaṇa" data-en="three characteristics">ti-lakkhaṇa</span>:
    <span class="pali" data-pali="anicca" data-en="impermanence">anicca</span>,
    <span class="pali" data-pali="dukkha" data-en="suffering; unsatisfactoriness">dukkha</span>,
    and <span class="pali" data-pali="anattā" data-en="non-self">anattā</span>.
    They are not a syllabus of separate insights. They are one diagnosis, turned
    so that the same conditioned stream can be seen from three angles.
  </p>

  <hr>

  <h2>Not a Checklist</h2>

  <p>
    It is easy to meet the three marks as a quiz. Can one define impermanence?
    Recite the types of
    <span class="pali" data-pali="dukkha" data-en="suffering; unsatisfactoriness">dukkha</span>?
    Affirm non-self without sounding nihilistic? Agreement arrives quickly.
    Most people already know, in principle, that bodies age, pleasures fade, and
    moods refuse orders. The difficulty is operational. The mind keeps relating
    to conditioned things as if they were permanent enough to lean on, satisfying
    enough to settle craving, and owned by a stable someone who is having them.
  </p>

  <p>
    The teaching does not ask for a new opinion about the cosmos. It asks whether
    that habit of relating survives careful looking. The Dhammapada's formulation
    is blunt:
  </p>

  <blockquote>
    "All formations are impermanent. All formations are suffering.
    All phenomena are non-self."
    <cite>— Dhp 277–279 (adapted)</cite>
  </blockquote>

  <p>
    The slight asymmetry in the third line — "phenomena"
    (<span class="pali" data-pali="dhamma" data-en="phenomena; teachings">dhammā</span>)
    rather than "formations"
    (<span class="pali" data-pali="saṅkhārā" data-en="conditioned formations">saṅkhārā</span>)
    — is worth holding lightly, but it is not incidental. Impermanence and
    unsatisfactoriness are said of conditioned things; non-self is applied more
    widely. There is no permanent owner to be found anywhere in experience —
    including in the search for one.
  </p>

  <hr>

  <h2>The Mismatch That Costs</h2>

  <p>
    Suffering, in the ordinary sense, needs no Buddhist vocabulary: pain, loss,
    insult, illness. The three characteristics point past that inventory to a
    structural mismatch. Conditioned phenomena arise and pass.
    <span class="pali" data-pali="vedanā" data-en="feeling-tone">Vedanā</span>
    flips — pleasant, unpleasant, neutral — often within a single hour. Thoughts
    appear without being summoned and leave without permission. And yet the mind
    keeps treating the stream as if something in it could be made to stay, as if
    the next arrangement would finally settle what today's could not, as if a
    solid "I" were the proprietor of the whole show.
  </p>

  <p>
    That mismatch is not a moral failure. It is the default setting of an
    untrained attention. The first noble truth does not claim that happiness is
    impossible, or that pleasant moments are fake. It claims that conditioned
    things — however lovely — cannot deliver the unconditional stability the mind
    is implicitly seeking when it reaches for them. The quarrel is not with
    pleasure. The quarrel is with the demand that pleasure hold still.
  </p>

  <p>
    Seeing the three marks clearly is, in a direct sense, the correction of that
    demand. Not by deciding to be resigned, but by noticing what was never stable
    enough to bargain with in the first place.
  </p>

  <hr>

  <h2>How One Mark Leads to the Next</h2>

  <p>
    The characteristics are interrelated, not merely parallel. There is a sequence
    running through them: it is <em>because</em> things change that they cannot
    provide lasting satisfaction; and it is <em>because</em> they change and cannot
    satisfy that they cannot constitute — or belong to — a permanent self. The
    sequence also describes how confusion thickens: take the impermanent as
    permanent, the unsatisfactory as finally satisfying, the ownerless as owned.
  </p>

  <h3><span class="pali" data-pali="anicca" data-en="impermanence">Anicca</span> — Impermanence</h3>

  <p>
    <span class="pali" data-pali="anicca" data-en="impermanence">Anicca</span>
    is the most immediately checkable of the three. Every conditioned thing arises
    in dependence on conditions and passes when those conditions shift. Breath
    turns. Sensation flickers. The body that woke this morning is not quite the
    body that will sleep tonight. Intellectual assent is cheap here. What matters
    is whether change is seen while it is happening — in the rising and falling of
    contact, not only in the abstract knowledge that "everything changes."
  </p>

  <p>
    When impermanence is noticed directly, grasping softens for a simple reason:
    the thing being held is already leaving. Letting go is not always a decision.
    Sometimes it is what attention does when it stops pretending the object was
    fixed.
  </p>

  <h3><span class="pali" data-pali="dukkha" data-en="suffering; unsatisfactoriness">Dukkha</span> — Unsatisfactoriness</h3>

  <p>
    <span class="pali" data-pali="dukkha" data-en="suffering; unsatisfactoriness">Dukkha</span>
    is usually rendered "suffering," but the Pali covers more ground than the
    English word. The commentarial tradition distinguishes three faces:
  </p>
  <ul>
    <li><em>dukkha-dukkha</em> — the direct sting of pain, illness, loss, and grief</li>
    <li><em>vipariṇāma-dukkha</em> — the ache that arrives when pleasant things change</li>
    <li><em>saṅkhāra-dukkha</em> — the pervasive contingency of conditioned existence itself, whether any given moment feels good or bad</li>
  </ul>

  <p>
    It is the third that distinguishes the Buddhist diagnosis from ordinary
    unhappiness. Even when life is going well — when the wanted thing has arrived —
    an undercurrent remains: this depends on conditions that will not stay. The
    pleasant is pleasant. It is not permanently pleasant. That is not a counsel of
    despair. It is a refusal to ask the conditioned to do the work of the
    unconditioned.
  </p>

  <h3><span class="pali" data-pali="anattā" data-en="non-self">Anattā</span> — Non-self</h3>

  <p>
    <span class="pali" data-pali="anattā" data-en="non-self">Anattā</span>
    is the easiest of the three to mishear as a slogan — either "you do not exist,"
    or an interesting idea that never interrupts the next surge of ownership. Neither
    reading does the work. In the Indian context, a genuine
    <span class="pali" data-pali="attā" data-en="self">attā</span>
    would need to be permanent, under control, and the ultimate subject of
    experience. The Buddha's challenge, applied aggregate by aggregate in the
    <a href="/suttas/anattalakkhana/"><em>Anattalakkhaṇa Sutta</em></a>, is exact:
    if form is impermanent, and therefore unsatisfactory, can it rightly be called
    mine, what I am, my self? The same questions land on feeling, perception,
    formations, and consciousness. In each case, the answer is no.
  </p>

  <p>
    This is not a claim that experience is not occurring, or that conventional
    persons disappear from ethics. It is a claim about what careful looking finds:
    a process — conditioned, changing, without a stable center that owns or
    commands it. The <em>idea</em> of a self arises within experience; it is not a
    knower standing safely behind the stream. The nihilistic reading is one the
    Buddha rejected. What anattā asks beyond the conceptual claim is the subject of
    <a href="/concepts/anatta-in-practice/">Anattā in Practice</a>; the map of the
    heaps themselves is
    <a href="/concepts/khandhas/">Khandhas</a>.
  </p>

  <hr>

  <h2>Seen, Not Merely Granted</h2>

  <p>
    The three characteristics are qualities to be investigated, not propositions to
    be stored. The
    <span class="pali" data-pali="satipaṭṭhāna" data-en="foundations of mindfulness">satipaṭṭhāna</span>
    training in <a href="/suttas/satipatthana/">MN 10</a> is, in large part, a
    structured way to look: body, feeling-tone, mind states, and phenomena — known
    as they arise, as they are present, as they pass. The instruction is not to
    meditate while holding "everything is impermanent" as a background belief. It
    is to observe carefully enough that change, contingency, and the absence of a
    fixed owner are <em>seen</em>.
  </p>

  <p>
    The difference matters. A conclusion held as a view can be argued with,
    qualified, or forgotten by lunch. A characteristic noticed in the body of
    experience becomes harder to unsee — and that noticing is what loosens the
    mismatch. A practitioner who sees
    <span class="pali" data-pali="anicca" data-en="impermanence">anicca</span>
    clearly will notice the dukkha of grasping what is already leaving. Noticing
    that, the question of a fixed grasper becomes less theoretical. The three
    illuminate each other in contact, not only when arranged as ideas.
  </p>

  <p>
    Nothing here is final. The marks can be understood at several depths, and the
    mind that glimpses them still returns to habit — a pattern traced more fully in
    <a href="/concepts/insight-cycles/">Insight Cycles</a>. What the teaching keeps
    offering is simpler than a finished metaphysics: stop asking the flux to be
    what it is not, and watch what happens to the quarrel when attention stops
    insisting.
  </p>

</article>
